comment.body:
@Kaffie: Thanks for replying!  Yeah, I don't see a way around videos, but it might be possible to reduce the db/cached data.  For large datasets like videos, I wonder if it would be useful to allow users to set a water level and then a "garbage collector" could clean up older data for systems with small storage.  For people who have large storage, they can set it much higher.

I've also wondered if it should use parity files like in the old USENET days.  Smaller storage systems could contribute by storing parity files (which take less space) and then if something is missing, the parity file could be requested so the file could be completed.

Finally, with that much storage use it will be difficult to have mobile clients.  Even if someone puts a 256GB card in their phone they won't be able to serve that much data.  So I think it would be good to solve this problem in the general case.
